287
00:16:57,750 --> 00:17:00,275
- This is nothing.
- Give it a second.

288
00:17:00,386 --> 00:17:03,184
- [Webb] 250 seconds is all we can do?
- [man] That's the maximum.

289
00:17:03,288 --> 00:17:05,688
- And you know that...
- [Webb] Did you talk to TRW?

290
00:17:05,791 --> 00:17:08,385
- [Owen] Who's the other voice?
- [Matt] I don't know.

291
00:17:08,494 --> 00:17:10,462
[man]...about their fuels.
So we're in trouble.

292
00:17:10,562 --> 00:17:11,961
[Webb]
Grumman has fucked us.

293
00:17:12,064 --> 00:17:15,329
They built a lander
that can't land.

294
00:17:15,434 --> 00:17:17,527
So, we are going back
for another prototype...

295
00:17:17,636 --> 00:17:19,035
With whom?

296
00:17:19,138 --> 00:17:21,038
This is setting us back four years.

297
00:17:21,140 --> 00:17:24,200
Well, I agree. This is going
to have to change.

298
00:17:24,309 --> 00:17:26,300
Change? We can't land
on the Moon.

299
00:17:26,412 --> 00:17:29,347
Unless by some miracle
Braun finds lighter fuel,

300
00:17:29,448 --> 00:17:32,281
- we aren't touching down for five years.
- Okay...

301
00:17:32,384 --> 00:17:34,648
We're just going to be circling
forever up there.

302
00:17:34,753 --> 00:17:36,345
So what are we telling everyone?

303
00:17:36,455 --> 00:17:38,423
- Nothing. We don't tell anyone--
- [recording stops]

304
00:17:39,458 --> 00:17:40,425
[sighs]

305
00:17:40,526 --> 00:17:42,221
[Matt] Do you understand
what this means?

306
00:17:42,327 --> 00:17:44,158
NASA can't do it.

307
00:17:44,263 --> 00:17:46,561
They can't land man
and come back.

308
00:17:46,665 --> 00:17:47,654
Have you called Brackett?

309
00:17:47,766 --> 00:17:49,927
Of course not!
I needed to tell you guys first.

310
00:17:50,035 --> 00:17:51,400
We need to tell Brackett.
We need to tell Brackett right away.

311
00:17:51,503 --> 00:17:53,300
This is something you report right away.
We need help.

312
00:17:53,405 --> 00:17:56,374
- We have to...
- Relax, it's okay. Yes. Yes.

313
00:17:56,475 --> 00:17:57,737
- And we need...
- I'll tell you what to do, okay?

314
00:17:57,843 --> 00:17:59,071
I'm gonna tell you what to do.

315
00:17:59,178 --> 00:18:01,373
Find out who that other guy
on that phone was, okay?

316
00:18:01,480 --> 00:18:03,448
Because, if we found this out
in a month,

317
00:18:03,549 --> 00:18:06,074
you better fucking believe that the mole
can do the same thing.

318
00:18:06,185 --> 00:18:08,312
And now all of a sudden the Russians
know we can't make it to the Moon,

319
00:18:08,420 --> 00:18:09,717
then what the fuck are
we going to do?

320
00:18:09,822 --> 00:18:13,121
Okay. Okay. Okay.
You call Langley.

321
00:18:14,960 --> 00:18:16,188
It's ringing.

322
00:18:16,295 --> 00:18:18,126
[line ringing]

323
00:18:18,230 --> 00:18:21,563
You think I'll get to talk
to the President? No.

324
00:18:21,667 --> 00:18:24,261
That's not unrealistic.
I could.

325
00:18:24,369 --> 00:18:25,961
He could be like, "We need to get this
right to the President."

326
00:18:26,071 --> 00:18:28,665
I'll be like, "All right. Give me
his home phone, sir. I'll..." [laughs]

327
00:18:28,774 --> 00:18:30,264
- [all laughing]
- [line continues ringing]

328
00:18:30,375 --> 00:18:31,603
[Brackett on phone]
Hello?

329
00:18:31,710 --> 00:18:33,905
Director Brackett, it's Agent Johnson
calling from Houston.

330
00:18:34,012 --> 00:18:35,070
We have big news.

331
00:18:35,180 --> 00:18:36,772
What's that?

332
00:18:36,882 --> 00:18:39,112
They can't make it to the Moon.

333
00:18:39,218 --> 00:18:43,177
We intercepted a call
from Jim Webb.

334
00:18:43,288 --> 00:18:45,722
From what I understand,
they can circle the Moon,

335
00:18:45,824 --> 00:18:47,519
but they can't actually land.

336
00:18:47,626 --> 00:18:49,685
They-- they don't have
the technology to do it.

337
00:18:49,795 --> 00:18:52,127
They're saying 1971
at the earliest.

338
00:18:52,231 --> 00:18:55,792
[Brackett sighs]
Damn it. Give me a minute.

339
00:18:58,403 --> 00:19:00,462
Okay, who else
knows about this?

340
00:19:00,572 --> 00:19:03,803
Uh, nobody, from-- from--
from what we can tell.

341
00:19:03,909 --> 00:19:06,139
They're talking about it on the phone
like it was a big secret,

342
00:19:06,245 --> 00:19:09,078
like they've never talked about it before.

343
00:19:09,181 --> 00:19:11,240
Okay, good.

344
00:19:11,350 --> 00:19:13,409
Another unit is going
to take over Zipper.

345
00:19:13,519 --> 00:19:15,146
Get your team out of there.

346
00:19:15,254 --> 00:19:20,692
Uh... You think maybe that's a bit, uh,
shortsighted in a way,

347
00:19:20,792 --> 00:19:23,420
seeing as we're here undercover now?
What-- Why?

348
00:19:23,529 --> 00:19:26,362
Don't question my orders, kid.

349
00:19:26,465 --> 00:19:28,365
I'm not-- I don't mean
to question it. I--

350
00:19:28,467 --> 00:19:31,630
I just-- I simply think
that we're here

351
00:19:31,737 --> 00:19:35,195
and I-- We have to figure out
a response to this,

352
00:19:35,307 --> 00:19:37,275
- somehow, and you've got us...
- [line disconnects]

353
00:19:37,376 --> 00:19:38,468
[dial tone]

354
00:19:42,381 --> 00:19:43,370
We're going home.

355
00:19:51,490 --> 00:19:52,457
[sighs]

356
00:20:05,237 --> 00:20:06,226
[sighs]

357
00:20:28,694 --> 00:20:30,662
♪♪

358
00:20:55,921 --> 00:20:58,890
[music continues]

359
00:21:50,876 --> 00:21:54,243
[Matt] If either of us are talking, shoot.
I don't care how much film you burn,

360
00:21:54,346 --> 00:21:55,870
it doesn't matter.
Okay? It's going to save us.

361
00:21:55,981 --> 00:21:57,346
[Owen] What are we
doing in here?

362
00:21:57,449 --> 00:21:58,711
Sit down, just listen
to this, okay?

363
00:21:58,817 --> 00:22:00,546
Well...

364
00:22:00,652 --> 00:22:03,348
- Hold on a sec...
- Did you call Brackett last night?

365
00:22:03,455 --> 00:22:04,888
- Yes, all right?
- What did he say?

366
00:22:04,990 --> 00:22:06,924
Okay, turn this on.

367
00:22:07,025 --> 00:22:09,289
What did they say?

368
00:22:09,394 --> 00:22:11,692
I'm gonna tell you
what they said.

369
00:22:13,965 --> 00:22:16,900
- [Owen] Okay, it's on.
- [beeping]

370
00:22:17,002 --> 00:22:18,401
Okay, you hear that?

371
00:22:18,503 --> 00:22:20,300
- Yeah.
- [beeping continues]

372
00:22:22,040 --> 00:22:24,270
- You recognize it?
- Yeah.

373
00:22:25,377 --> 00:22:26,810
It's Sputnik.

374
00:22:26,912 --> 00:22:28,470
[stammers] You know what?
You're ahead of me.

375
00:22:28,580 --> 00:22:29,808
Okay, yeah.
It's Sputnik.

376
00:22:29,915 --> 00:22:31,746
How do you know
it's Sputnik?

377
00:22:31,850 --> 00:22:34,683
Can you... Did you
sleep here last night?

378
00:22:34,786 --> 00:22:38,017
[Matt] That's not plugged
into anything.

379
00:22:38,123 --> 00:22:40,591
It's-- it's just a dial on the other side.
It's not actually Sputnik.

380
00:22:40,692 --> 00:22:43,320
It's just making you think that it is.
It's just a random beeping.

381
00:22:43,428 --> 00:22:45,862
And because you think
that that's supposed to be Sputnik,

382
00:22:45,964 --> 00:22:47,488
that's why you believe
it's Sputnik.

383
00:22:47,599 --> 00:22:50,830
This is what we are
going to do with the Moon.

384
00:22:50,936 --> 00:22:52,369
I called Brackett,

385
00:22:52,471 --> 00:22:55,031
told him that they
can't make it for '69.

386
00:22:55,140 --> 00:22:58,303
He said, "Okay, well,
you've got to figure out a way to fix it."

387
00:22:58,410 --> 00:23:01,641
And I said, "We can do it on our own.

388
00:23:01,747 --> 00:23:05,581
"We can make a film that shows us
going to the Moon

389
00:23:05,684 --> 00:23:07,652
without actually doing it."

390
00:23:09,688 --> 00:23:11,679
We know that
they can make it up there.

391
00:23:11,790 --> 00:23:14,384
We're not-- We're faking
the last little piece.

392
00:23:14,493 --> 00:23:18,554
The tiny-- The tiny thing they can't do:
Land and come back.

393
00:23:18,663 --> 00:23:21,894
The thing JFK said we'd do.
That's the only part.

394
00:23:22,000 --> 00:23:24,400
Everything else is real,
do you understand?

395
00:23:24,503 --> 00:23:27,063
Yeah, I understand what you're saying
and I understand that it sounds like--

396
00:23:27,172 --> 00:23:28,639
Read this,
it's from Brackett.

397
00:23:28,740 --> 00:23:30,708
- He sent a briefing?
- Yes.

398
00:23:37,015 --> 00:23:38,949
If we can pull this off,

399
00:23:39,050 --> 00:23:42,042
we are going to look
like geniuses.

400
00:23:42,154 --> 00:23:45,248
Four guys inside of NASA figure out

401
00:23:45,357 --> 00:23:47,825
[whispering] how to make it look
like we went to the Moon. We did it.

402
00:23:47,926 --> 00:23:49,917
That's crazy!

403
00:23:50,028 --> 00:23:52,155
This is exactly what
we've been waiting for.

404
00:23:52,264 --> 00:23:54,892
It literally fell on our lap.

405
00:23:56,601 --> 00:23:59,900
We could run our own department
after something like this.

406
00:24:01,740 --> 00:24:03,708
♪♪

407
00:24:42,781 --> 00:24:45,011
[Owen] Is there
more information coming?

408
00:24:45,116 --> 00:24:47,550
[Matt] About what?

409
00:24:47,652 --> 00:24:50,644
Well, the objectives
and the budget.

410
00:24:50,755 --> 00:24:52,882
Why?

411
00:24:52,991 --> 00:24:55,050
This doesn't seem
incomplete to you?

412
00:24:55,160 --> 00:24:57,720
Incomplete? How?
What do you mean?

413
00:24:57,829 --> 00:24:59,660
Well, I-- Okay...

414
00:24:59,764 --> 00:25:01,698
You know what? Don't--
don't worry about this.

415
00:25:01,800 --> 00:25:04,598
They obviously told us exactly
what they want us to hear,

416
00:25:04,703 --> 00:25:08,400
so our job is to film a test,
and that's it.

417
00:25:08,507 --> 00:25:10,168
Come on.

418
00:25:12,177 --> 00:25:15,544
[Owen] Does it-- You don't have
an ethical problem with this at all?

419
00:25:17,148 --> 00:25:19,742
In what way?

420
00:25:19,851 --> 00:25:21,284
In that this is lying.

421
00:25:22,687 --> 00:25:24,712
You know what? This is like one
of those good lies,

422
00:25:24,823 --> 00:25:26,882
like Santa Claus
and the Easter Bunny.

423
00:25:26,992 --> 00:25:29,051
[straining] A lot of kids get really
mad about those.

424
00:25:29,160 --> 00:25:30,491
[grunts]

425
00:25:30,595 --> 00:25:31,994
[both laugh]

426
00:25:33,031 --> 00:25:35,522
So we're shooting this
at 48 frames a second,

427
00:25:35,634 --> 00:25:39,468
so you're going to have to move like...
like you're being lifted up.

428
00:25:39,571 --> 00:25:41,835
- Okay? Like this...
- This thing weighs about 100 pounds.

429
00:25:41,940 --> 00:25:43,669
Well, just try it.
Try leaping a bit.

430
00:25:43,775 --> 00:25:44,742
Like this.

431
00:25:53,285 --> 00:25:54,582
Yeah, good.

432
00:25:54,686 --> 00:25:56,381
Go! Action! Action!

433
00:25:59,157 --> 00:26:01,091
[Jared] More that way.

434
00:26:01,192 --> 00:26:02,625
[Matt]
More towards me a bit.

435
00:26:02,727 --> 00:26:04,524
[Jared]
Walk off that way.

436
00:26:04,629 --> 00:26:06,529
[Matt] Wait a minute.
Wait a minute. Wait a minute.

437
00:26:06,631 --> 00:26:07,996
Stop.

438
00:26:09,034 --> 00:26:10,695
[panting]

439
00:26:13,238 --> 00:26:15,331
We should be doing this at night.

440
00:26:15,440 --> 00:26:17,465
