00:42:13,230 --> 00:42:15,061
Right.
Check the gate, Doug.

735
00:42:15,165 --> 00:42:17,133
[chattering]

736
00:42:33,050 --> 00:42:35,610
I would never normally do this,
but it's for a friend.

737
00:42:35,719 --> 00:42:38,688
- His name is Matt Johnson.
- Mm-hmm.

738
00:42:46,931 --> 00:42:50,094
[Matt] Jared, tell me
you are getting this.

739
00:42:50,200 --> 00:42:53,135
Oh, my God.
Excuse me?

740
00:42:53,237 --> 00:42:56,866
How, um... how'd you set this up?

741
00:42:58,576 --> 00:43:01,010
Owen, it's called
front screen projection!

742
00:43:01,111 --> 00:43:02,476
We got it!

743
00:43:04,748 --> 00:43:07,046
Kubrick's technique,
how he's faking...

744
00:43:09,186 --> 00:43:11,154
I wanna--
I wanna tell you.

745
00:43:18,796 --> 00:43:22,232
Boles, hey. It's called
front screen projection.

746
00:43:22,333 --> 00:43:24,198
We figured out how to--
how to do it.

747
00:43:26,203 --> 00:43:28,797
Yeah, okay, all right.
I'll, uh...

748
00:43:28,906 --> 00:43:30,874
Do you want us
to fly right there, or...?

749
00:43:33,644 --> 00:43:34,611
Sure.

750
00:43:35,913 --> 00:43:36,880
[receiver clicks]

751
00:43:48,092 --> 00:43:50,993
All right, it's called
front screen projection.

752
00:43:51,095 --> 00:43:54,087
Stanley Kubrick can fake
any environment he wants,

753
00:43:54,198 --> 00:43:56,996
by projecting it
through a semi-transparent mirror

754
00:43:57,101 --> 00:43:59,763
and then onto a gigantic silver screen.

755
00:43:59,870 --> 00:44:03,135
Then he films the entire scene
through the same mirror

756
00:44:03,240 --> 00:44:05,731
at a 90-degree angle
to the projector.

757
00:44:05,843 --> 00:44:09,142
What it winds up doing
is creating images

758
00:44:09,246 --> 00:44:13,580
where you can't tell
where the stage stops...

759
00:44:15,185 --> 00:44:18,279
and the fake photographic
background begins.

760
00:44:18,389 --> 00:44:20,584
You have an infinite depth of field

761
00:44:20,691 --> 00:44:26,095
into environments that exist completely
in two-dimensional space.

762
00:44:26,196 --> 00:44:29,563
We can do the same thing
with the lunar surface photography

763
00:44:29,667 --> 00:44:32,158
that NASA is taking
on the Apollo missions.

764
00:44:32,269 --> 00:44:33,531
[projector clicking]

765
00:44:33,637 --> 00:44:36,265
♪♪

766
00:44:36,373 --> 00:44:39,934
Movie special effects
can be very convincing,

767
00:44:40,044 --> 00:44:44,140
especially when you don't know you're
watching a movie.

768
00:44:44,248 --> 00:44:47,342
The plan is to rent
a film studio in Texas,

769
00:44:47,451 --> 00:44:51,911
hire a crew, and have them build
our own lunar lander.

770
00:44:52,022 --> 00:44:56,118
We'll mix this practical set piece,
with Kubrick's projection technique,

771
00:44:56,226 --> 00:45:00,026
and presto, the illusion that man
is walking on the Moon.

772
00:45:00,130 --> 00:45:02,860
Now I know you're probably thinking
this is too much exposure,

773
00:45:02,966 --> 00:45:05,867
and that the risk of bringing in outsiders
is too high,

774
00:45:05,969 --> 00:45:08,961
but we already have the perfect cover.

775
00:45:09,073 --> 00:45:12,668
We're making a documentary
about the Moon landing.

776
00:45:12,776 --> 00:45:15,677
And it's not a stretch to say that we're
building sets to conduct interviews,

777
00:45:15,779 --> 00:45:17,144
shoot B-roll footage.

778
00:45:17,247 --> 00:45:19,112
We could even say
it's for simulations.

779
00:45:19,216 --> 00:45:22,242
Hell, most of the major networks
are doing this already.

780
00:45:22,352 --> 00:45:26,152
The only people who need to know what's
actually happening are the astronauts,

781
00:45:26,256 --> 00:45:28,816
who you should select
based on their willingness to cooperate,

782
00:45:28,926 --> 00:45:32,259
and James Webb, who's either
going to have to work with us

783
00:45:32,362 --> 00:45:34,023
or get out of the way.

784
00:45:35,099 --> 00:45:36,088
And that's the easy part.

785
00:45:36,200 --> 00:45:38,191
We also need to convince
everybody at NASA.

786
00:45:38,302 --> 00:45:41,066
The good news is, the only people
who are in contact with the rocket

787
00:45:41,171 --> 00:45:44,299
are all in one room in Houston,
inside Mission Control.

788
00:45:45,476 --> 00:45:48,934
If we can convince Mission Control
that what they're doing is real,

789
00:45:49,046 --> 00:45:52,015
everybody else will follow.
How do we do that?

790
00:45:52,116 --> 00:45:54,744
Well, Mission Control
actually monitors everything,

791
00:45:54,852 --> 00:45:56,251
from the heart rates
of the astronauts,

792
00:45:56,353 --> 00:46:00,119
to the exact location of the lunar module
as it descends to the Moon.

793
00:46:00,224 --> 00:46:03,921
And they're getting all this information
through radio, directly from the ship.

794
00:46:04,027 --> 00:46:08,862
The good news is that they've run
so many tests with this exact mission

795
00:46:08,966 --> 00:46:12,561
that they actually have telemetric data
of successful lunar landings,

796
00:46:12,669 --> 00:46:16,730
stored on guidance systems
on Apollo 11.

797
00:46:18,108 --> 00:46:19,973
Here's where we get very lucky.

798
00:46:20,077 --> 00:46:23,012
As the command module passes along
to the dark side of the Moon,

799
00:46:23,113 --> 00:46:26,048
the radio signals
can't penetrate the core.

800
00:46:26,150 --> 00:46:28,243
For 30 minutes, we have a window

801
00:46:28,352 --> 00:46:32,982
for the astronauts to switch
from real data to fake telemetric data.

802
00:46:33,090 --> 00:46:36,150
Mission control will be getting
data of the lunar module

803
00:46:36,260 --> 00:46:38,922
undocking and landing
on the lunar surface,

804
00:46:39,029 --> 00:46:41,463
but it will be completely faked.

805
00:46:41,565 --> 00:46:43,465
Combine that with our footage

806
00:46:43,567 --> 00:46:46,764
that the astronauts are going to pipe into
the broadcast back to Earth,

807
00:46:46,870 --> 00:46:48,531
and nobody's
going to have any idea.

808
00:46:49,573 --> 00:46:52,041
As far as NASA and the rest of the world
is concerned,

809
00:46:52,142 --> 00:46:54,337
the United States
just landed on the Moon.

810
00:46:54,444 --> 00:46:57,811
Finally, the broadcast.

811
00:46:57,915 --> 00:47:00,281
To shoot in slow motion,
we have to shoot film.

812
00:47:00,384 --> 00:47:02,852
To broadcast,
it needs to be video.

813
00:47:02,953 --> 00:47:05,751
Which means we have to do a transfer,
which normally would be fine,

814
00:47:05,856 --> 00:47:09,724
except that people cannot know
it originally began as film.

815
00:47:09,827 --> 00:47:11,988
That means a single scratch,
any dust...

816
00:47:12,095 --> 00:47:13,926
[Brackett] Okay, okay.
We got it.

817
00:47:14,031 --> 00:47:15,293
Thank you for the presentation.

818
00:47:15,399 --> 00:47:17,697
- You can go ahead.
- Thank you, sir.

819
00:47:17,801 --> 00:47:19,769
[softly] Talk to your folks
about the Northwoods plan.

820
00:47:19,870 --> 00:47:23,966
Tell them to put a hold on it
and we'll see how this develops.

821
00:47:24,074 --> 00:47:26,201
Director, what is
the Northwoods plan?

822
00:47:26,310 --> 00:47:28,835
I've never heard of
Operation Northwoods.

823
00:47:28,946 --> 00:47:32,507
Shoot down Apollo 11
and blame the Soviets.

824
00:47:32,616 --> 00:47:35,847
[stammering]
With the astronauts on the flight?

825
00:47:35,953 --> 00:47:38,080
Why would we do that?

826
00:47:39,857 --> 00:47:42,155
If your film doesn't come together,

827
00:47:42,259 --> 00:47:44,784
then we have to have
a backup plan.

828
00:47:44,895 --> 00:47:47,022
And that is our backup plan.

829
00:47:57,107 --> 00:47:58,404
[whirring]

830
00:48:02,446 --> 00:48:04,880
...plan? I've never heard
of Operation Northwoods.

831
00:48:04,982 --> 00:48:08,110
Shoot down Apollo 11
and blame the Soviets.

832
00:48:08,218 --> 00:48:09,412
[clicks off]

833
00:48:16,994 --> 00:48:17,961
[whirring]

834
00:48:33,377 --> 00:48:35,777
[man on TV] Who were these men
going to the Moon?

835
00:48:35,879 --> 00:48:40,077
David Schoumacher profiled
the crew of Apollo 11.

836
00:48:41,118 --> 00:48:45,578
Neil Armstrong, the man chosen to be
first to step upon the Moon.

837
00:48:45,689 --> 00:48:51,491
He is by all accounts intelligent,
courteous, sober, a good family man.

838
00:48:51,595 --> 00:48:53,961
He is perfect for the role,

839
00:48:54,064 --> 00:48:58,330
beyond what a Hollywood scriptwriter
would dare.

840
00:48:58,435 --> 00:49:01,199
Buzz Aldrin is perhaps the most brilliant
of the astronauts,

841
00:49:01,305 --> 00:49:03,432
some say even a genius.

842
00:49:03,540 --> 00:49:08,136
His doctorate at MIT came after a thesis
on orbital rendezvous,

843
00:49:08,245 --> 00:49:13,945
and he understands the abstract theory
of space mechanics as well as anyone.

844
00:49:14,051 --> 00:49:18,920
Mike Collins is the least technical
in outlook of the Apollo 11 astronauts,

845
00:49:19,022 --> 00:49:20,546
but the most philosophical.

846
00:49:20,657 --> 00:49:22,522
If he does not love machines,

847
00:49:22,626 --> 00:49:26,585
he does love wine,
and books, and roses.

848
00:49:26,697 --> 00:49:29,359
A man who has known all three pilots
for many years

849
00:49:29,466 --> 00:49:31,957
says if he were
forced down on an island,

850
00:49:32,069 --> 00:49:36,005
he would want it to be with Collins
for the quality of his personality.

851
00:49:36,106 --> 00:49:39,564
Another said he would prefer Aldrin,
because, with his intelligence,

852
00:49:39,676 --> 00:49:41,906
he would soon be converting seawater
to fresh water

853
00:49:42,012 --> 00:49:44,378
and otherwise logically
attacking the problem.

854
00:49:44,481 --> 00:49:46,949
But both agreed
in the final analysis,

855
00:49:47,050 --> 00:49:50,110
that they would hope
it was with Armstrong,

856
00:49:50,220 --> 00:49:54,179
because, somehow,
he would get them off of it.

857
00:49:59,396 --> 00:50:01,193
[phone ringing]

858
00:50:01,298 --> 00:50:02,663
Hello?

859
00:50:02,766 --> 00:50:05,257
Boles, we just got back.
Where are you?

860
00:50:07,337 --> 00:50:09,567
Okay. Turn on the TV.

861
00:50:09,673 --> 00:50:12,801
Yeah, okay.
I'm turning it on now. Why?

862
00:50:12,909 --> 00:50:14,035
[reporter on TV]
Summarize what you just said,

863
00:50:14,144 --> 00:50:15,668
and then we'll ask you some questions
about seeing the President?

864
00:50:15,779 --> 00:50:20,443
Uh, yes, I'd like to say
that, uh, over a year ago,

865
00:50:20,550 --> 00:50:24,145
President Johnson and I
reviewed the space program

866
00:50:24,254 --> 00:50:27,485
and, uh, agreed to build strength

867
00:50:27,591 --> 00:50:31,152
so that I might retire
on my 62nd birthday,

868
00:50:31,261 --> 00:50:34,094
which happens to be
this next October 7th.

869
00:50:34,197 --> 00:50:37,325
Today, we have reviewed
the progress we have made

870
00:50:37,434 --> 00:50:42,235
and the President has agreed
that I could retire on October 7th,

871
00:50:42,339 --> 00:50:44,034
when I will be 62.

872
00:50:44,141 --> 00:50:46,006
- [Matt exhales]
- I'd like to say one other thing...

873
00:50:46,109 --> 00:50:50,239
Yeah, okay. Well, I guess that means
he didn't want to cooperate, huh?

874
00:50:50,347 --> 00:50:53,839
Okay, yeah. I'll see you
when you get back. Bye.

875
00:50:53,950 --> 00:50:55,577
[indistinct talking]

876
00:50:58,688 --> 00:51:00,087
[Matt] Andy!

877
00:51:03,226 --> 00:51:04,193
Sorry.

878
00:51:07,097 --> 00:51:09,497
- What are you doing?
- Shooting for the documentary.

879
00:51:09,599 --> 00:51:12,727
- Oh, okay, fine. Where's Owen?
- He's at the hospital.

880
00:51:12,836 --> 00:51:14,235
What?

881
00:51:15,439 --> 00:51:16,906
Julie had the baby.

882
00:51:17,007 --> 00:51:18,736
Oh, shit!

883
00:51:21,678 --> 00:51:23,373
Hey.

884
00:51:23,480 --> 00:51:25,072
I missed it, eh?

885
00:51:25,182 --> 00:51:26,740
Hey, Mom.

886
00:51:26,850 --> 00:51:28,442
Wow!

887
00:51:28,552 --> 00:51:29,541
[Owen] Matt!

888
00:51:29,653 --> 00:51:31,450
- What's his name?
- Simon.

889
00:51:31,555 --> 00:51:33,420
- Can I hold him?
- Sure, if you want to.

890
00:51:33,523 --> 00:51:35,047
[whispering] I need to talk to you.
I need to talk to Matt.

891
00:51:35,158 --> 00:51:36,785
[Matt whispering]
Okay. What's up?

892
00:51:38,762 --> 00:51:40,059
One minute.

893
00:51:42,099 --> 00:51:43,464
[Matt] Okay, okay.

894
00:51:45,102 --> 00:51:47,127
What the hell is this?

895
00:51:47,237 --> 00:51:50,365
Jared showed me the photos of the men
who were watching us at the barbecue.

896
00:51:50,474 --> 00:51:52,203
- They're filming us, Matt!
- Okay.

897
00:51:52,309 --> 00:51:54,573
Why are you bringing this up
at the hospital?

898
00:51:54,678 --> 00:51:57,772
- Relax!
- Relax? This could be the Russians!

899
00:51:57,881 --> 00:52:00,349
We have to get off this mission.

900
00:52:00,450 --> 00:52:05,046
If we get caught,
the CIA will abandon us, okay?

901
00:52:05,155 --> 00:52:07,419
- I'm calling Brackett to them him--
- No! No! No!

902
00:52:07,524 --> 00:52:10,084
You are not calling Brackett!
No one's calling Brackett!

903
00:52:10,193 --> 00:52:11,592
You are being paranoid!

904
00:52:11,695 --> 00:52:15,153
I hope so, because if I'm right
and this is the mole?

905
00:52:15,265 --> 00:52:18,166
If they find out what we are doing,
then we are fucking dead.

906
00:52:18,268 --> 00:52:19,428
You got that?

907
00:52:21,204 --> 00:52:22,466
♪♪

908
00:52:22,572 --> 00:52:25,097
♪ Keep on chooglin' ♪

909
00:52:25,208 --> 00:52:28,075
♪ Keep on chooglin' ♪

910
00:52:28,178 --> 00:52:30,078
♪ Keep on chooglin' ♪

911
00:52:30,180 --> 00:52:32,842
- ♪ Chooglin', chooglin' ♪
- [horn honking]

912
00:52:32,949 --> 00:52:35,645
♪ Chooglin', chooglin', chooglin',
chooglin' ♪

913
00:52:35,752 --> 00:52:40,416
♪ Oh... no, no, no ♪

914
00:52:40,524 --> 00:52:42,492
♪♪

915
00:52:57,841 --> 00:53:00,036
- [music stops]
- [car doors open]

916
00:53:02,913 --> 00:53:05,438
[car doors close]

917
00:53:05,549 --> 00:53:06,811
[Matt exhales]

918
00:53:12,822 --> 00:53:13,948
[chuckles]

919
00:53:21,731 --> 00:53:23,528
Looks pretty good.

920
00:53:23,633 --> 00:53:26,033
[Matt] "Looks pretty good"?
Guys, come on.

921
00:53:28,838 --> 00:53:30,601
- Are you kidding me?
- All right.

922
00:53:30,707 --> 00:53:33,471
This cost $45,000!

923
00:53:33,577 --> 00:53:34,771
- Really?
- Yeah!

924
00:53:34,878 --> 00:53:37,244
Oh, God, don't start that.

925
00:53:37,347 --> 00:53:39,372
"Really? Hey, you got ripped off.

926
00:53:39,482 --> 00:53:40,847
Hey, come on,
I could have done this..."

927
00:53:40,951 --> 00:53:44,250
- "I could've done it cheaper."
- "$20 and some elbow grease!"

928
00:53:44,354 --> 00:53:46,322
Do you think it would kill you to say,
"Good job, Matt"?

929
00:53:46,423 --> 00:53:48,414
[Boles chuckles]

930
00:53:48,525 --> 00:53:51,289
I mean that seriously. Do you think
it would physically kill you?

931
00:53:51,394 --> 00:53:53,385
Okay, and it's for a film shoot.

932
00:53:53,496 --> 00:53:55,794
Uh, we're making a documentary
about the Moon landing,

933
00:53:55,899 --> 00:53:57,764
and we need to make a lunar surface.

934
00:53:57,867 --> 00:54:01,359
And so it's like a fake lunar surface.
That's-- that's what we need.

935
00:54:01,471 --> 00:54:04,702
So I don't know how much sand
you can ship us.

936
00:54:04,808 --> 00:54:06,833
But, uh, four-- four tons?

937
00:54:06,943 --> 00:54:08,774
How many tons are in a truck?
Can you hold on a sec?

938
00:54:08,878 --> 00:54:10,743
Where are you going?

939
00:54:10,847 --> 00:54:12,712
Uh, sorry, say again?

940
00:54:12,816 --> 00:54:15,808
Actually, I went to a place in Arizona
called Cinder Lake,

941
00:54:15,919 --> 00:54:20,253
where the sand was brown as molasses.
It was beautiful.

942
00:54:20,357 --> 00:54:23,758
It was a beautiful brown.
Molten brown.

943
00:54:23,860 --> 00:54:25,828
♪♪

944
00:54:30,934 --> 00:54:33,528
So, what are these guys gonna say
when they're up here?

945
00:54:33,637 --> 00:54:36,162
We need something they can print
as a headline.

946
00:54:36,273 --> 00:54:38,833
Type out a couple things and let's just
see what we got, okay?

947
00:54:38,942 --> 00:54:42,434
So try this:
"Welcome to the Moon."

948
00:54:43,480 --> 00:54:45,573
Catch!
[laughing]

949
00:54:45,682 --> 00:54:47,912
So, no, leave that where it was,
it's my A rock.

950
00:54:48,018 --> 00:54:50,077
I think if we never say
the word "America."

951
00:54:50,186 --> 00:54:51,949
[Boles] Oh, yeah, we just take
an American symbol.

952
00:54:52,055 --> 00:54:54,148
Exactly. Eagle. Freedom.

953
00:54:54,257 --> 00:54:56,282
- [Boles] Frontier.
- Frontier.

954
00:54:56,393 --> 00:55:00,022
So that needs to make
that pothole there.

955
00:55:00,130 --> 00:55:01,324
Does that have
a label on it?

956
00:55:01,431 --> 00:55:05,197
B. So that goes
right at your feet. Perfect.

957
00:55:05,302 --> 00:55:08,203
I just got an idea. You know what we've
gotta have them do when they're up there?

958
00:55:08,305 --> 00:55:09,795
Who is it, Galileo
or somebody, said...

959
00:55:09,906 --> 00:55:12,306
- [Boles] Oh, drop the feather.
- Drop the feather and the hammer?

960
00:55:12,409 --> 00:55:13,842
And he said, in a vacuum,

961
00:55:13,943 --> 00:55:16,241
a hammer and a feather
would fall at the same speed.

962
00:55:16,346 --> 00:55:17,938
Well, okay, but how
are we gonna do that?

963
00:55:18,048 --> 00:55:19,913
A lead feather.

964
00:55:20,016 --> 00:55:22,678
Wait a minute, we gotta keep the flag
as stable as possible,

965
00:55:22,786 --> 00:55:25,311
because the wind resistance
makes it billow.

966
00:55:25,422 --> 00:55:27,151
- You wave the flag.
- You can't do that!

967
00:55:27,257 --> 00:55:28,918
Okay, Houston,
I'm about to step off the LM.

968
00:55:29,025 --> 00:55:32,188
- He leaves a footprint there.
- 'Cause they'd leave footprints there.

969
00:55:32,295 --> 00:55:35,287
Exactly! And we so can send
photographs of that back home.

970
00:55:35,398 --> 00:55:37,730
It's-- That's--
That is the image!

971
00:55:37,834 --> 00:55:39,165
Write that down,
the footprints!

972
00:55:39,269 --> 00:55:41,703
The word "foot" is disgusting.

973
00:55:41,805 --> 00:55:43,363
Maybe people
don't want to hear "foot," but--

974
00:55:43,473 --> 00:55:45,566
No, "with this step." You would say,
"With this step."

975
00:55:45,675 --> 00:55:46,801
"With this step!"

976
00:55:47,844 --> 00:55:51,245
Okay, okay. "With this step, I..."

977
00:55:51,348 --> 00:55:53,748
[Boles] No. "As man walks
on the Moon..."

978
00:55:53,850 --> 00:55:55,943
[Matt] Too literal. Too literal!

979
00:55:56,052 --> 00:55:57,349
[Boles] "The step of a single man..."

980
00:55:57,454 --> 00:55:59,319
- [Matt] "The step of a single man.
- [Boles] "But for..."

981
00:55:59,422 --> 00:56:00,480
[Matt] "But for us back at home..."

982
00:56:00,590 --> 00:56:02,421
Think of what
a step is like to us.

983
00:56:02,525 --> 00:56:04,356
To a man,
a step is just a step.

984
00:56:04,461 --> 00:56:07,760
But to an ant looking up at the man,
he looks like a God.

985
00:56:07,864 --> 00:56:09,024
And it doesn't
look like a step,

986
00:56:09,132 --> 00:56:13,000
it looks like
a towering leap.

987
00:56:15,939 --> 00:56:17,930
[typewriter clacking]

988
00:56:18,041 --> 00:56:20,009
It's like a leap. It's like a jump.

989
00:56:20,110 --> 00:56:21,941
[Boles] And this is a leap forward for...

990
00:56:22,045 --> 00:56:24,206
- [Matt] For everything!
- [Boles]...the next evolutionary step.

991
00:56:24,314 --> 00:56:25,406
[Matt] A leap forward in science.

992
00:56:25,515 --> 00:56:27,483
- [Boles] For humanity.
- [Matt] Exactly!

993
00:56:27,584 --> 00:56:29,518
♪♪

994
00:56:40,997 --> 00:56:42,294
This is good.

995
00:56:44,701 --> 00:56:46,134
[door opens]

996
00:56:48,104 --> 00:56:49,366
[door closes]

997
00:56:49,472 --> 00:56:51,269
- Okay, let's try one.
- [Owen] Hey!

998
00:56:52,809 --> 00:56:54,902
- Do you know who that is outside?
- [Boles] Who?

999
00:56:56,713 --> 00:56:58,613
Right there.

1000
00:56:58,715 --> 00:57:00,046
- Look.
- Where?

1001
00:57:00,150 --> 00:57:02,880
Tell me whose that is.

1002
00:57:02,986 --> 00:57:04,749
[Matt] Is he running?

1003
00:57:04,854 --> 00:57:06,685
Did you say "hi"? Did he look at you
when you came in?

1004
00:57:06,790 --> 00:57:08,758
- [Boles] Is there even a guy in there?
- [Owen] He's sitting there watching.

1005
00:57:08,858 --> 00:57:11,418
- [Boles] Shh. Shh.
- Go outside, you'll see.

1006
00:57:11,528 --> 00:57:13,359
I'm sure he works for the studio.
I'll go talk to him.

1007
00:57:13,463 --> 00:57:15,397
They know we're here.
We're allowed to be here, okay?

1008
00:57:15,498 --> 00:57:16,624
Relax.

1009
00:57:16,733 --> 00:57:17,927
[sighs] Okay.

1010
00:57:21,438 --> 00:57:23,338
Hi.

1011
00:57:23,440 --> 00:57:24,600
[car engine starts]

1012
00:57:25,642 --> 00:57:27,303
[tires screeching]

1013
00:57:28,445 --> 00:57:29,969
[Matt] Go, go, go, go!

1014
00:57:31,548 --> 00:57:33,072
Jared, get in the car!

1015
00:57:34,751 --> 00:57:35,945
[car doors slamming]

1016
00:57:42,892 --> 00:57:44,553
Boles, what are you doing?

1017
00:57:44,661 --> 00:57:46,856
[tires screeching]

1018
00:57:46,963 --> 00:57:50,262
- What happened?
- You shot your fucking gun!

1019
00:57:51,468 --> 00:57:54,198
Jared, shoot out the front!
Try to get their license plate!

1020
00:57:55,839 --> 00:57:58,865
- [engine backfires]
- Come on!

1021
00:57:58,975 --> 00:58:00,909
- No!
- [Jared] What?

1022
00:58:01,010 --> 00:58:02,807
[engine stalling]

1023
00:58:02,912 --> 00:58:03,879
[crash]

1024
00:58:08,952 --> 00:58:10,544
[Owen] What happened?

1025
00:58:10,653 --> 00:58:12,086
[Boles] What happened to your car?

1026
00:58:12,188 --> 00:58:14,656
It stalled.
They got away.

1027
00:58:14,757 --> 00:58:16,384
[Boles] Well, did you get a look at them?

1028
00:58:18,228 --> 00:58:20,128
Whoever it is,
they know we're here.

1029
00:58:20,230 --> 00:58:21,390
Well, we don't know who it is.

1030
00:58:21,498 --> 00:58:23,125
I think it's the mole.

1031
00:58:23,233 --> 00:58:25,701
I think it's the mole that you guys
sent us here to find in the first place.

1032
00:58:25,802 --> 00:58:27,201
Who else is waiting outside the studio

1033
00:58:27,303 --> 00:58:28,930
- and then the minute we walk out...
- Let's lock it up.

1034
00:58:29,038 --> 00:58:30,596
Let's lock it up and call Brackett.

1035
00:58:30,707 --> 00:58:33,608
What-- Lock it up? We're in the middle
of this! We can't just stop shooting!

1036
00:58:33,710 --> 00:58:35,575
Well, there might be
guys on the roof.

1037
00:58:35,678 --> 00:58:37,908
What do you mean, guys on the roof?
What the fuck is going on?

1038
00:58:38,014 --> 00:58:39,106
And what, you got a gun?

1039
00:58:39,282 --> 00:58:41,773
[man on TV]
This is CBS News special report.

1040
00:58:41,885 --> 00:58:43,546
The Flight of Apollo 8.

1041
00:58:43,653 --> 00:58:45,120
Six days
to the Moon and back.

1042
00:58:45,221 --> 00:58:47,519
Brought to you
by Walter Cronkite.

1043
00:58:47,624 --> 00:58:50,525
The flight of Apollo 8 is over.

1044
00:58:50,627 --> 00:58:54,063
And all that remains is to remove
the astronauts from the space craft,

1045
00:58:54,163 --> 00:58:59,430
and carry them less than two miles
to the deck of the carrier Yorktown.

1046
00:58:59,536 --> 00:59:02,061
Future plans for space missions,
of course,

1047
00:59:02,171 --> 00:59:04,765
have been accelerated considerably.

1048
00:59:04,874 --> 00:59:08,105
It means that they can keep
to the hoped-for schedule

1049
00:59:08,211 --> 00:59:14,673
of the next Apollo 9 mission,
late in February or early in March,

1050
00:59:14,784 --> 00:59:17,150
to test out the landing module,

1051
00:59:17,253 --> 00:59:20,745
and, uh, then move on towards
landing a man on the Moon

1052
00:59:20,857 --> 00:59:23,985
two flights further on
in the middle of July.

1053
00:59:25,795 --> 00:59:29,663
[Boles] So we've got
good news and bad news.

1054
00:59:29,766 --> 00:59:34,203
The good news: his name
is Antonin Lhotsky.

1055
00:59:34,304 --> 00:59:36,864
- [Matt] Uh-huh.
- [Boles] He's a KGB agent.

1056
00:59:36,973 --> 00:59:38,838
He's the man from outside the studio
the other night.

1057
00:59:38,942 --> 00:59:39,966
Whoa, what?

1058
00:59:40,076 --> 00:59:42,977
We suspect he's been the mole
the entire time.

1059
00:59:43,079 --> 00:59:45,877
S-- so then he knows
about Avalanche. We're fucked!

1060
00:59:45,982 --> 00:59:47,108
We don't think he does.

1061
00:59:47,216 --> 00:59:49,582
We've been interrogating him
for the past couple of days.

1062
00:59:49,686 --> 00:59:53,213
He doesn't seem to know anything.
We've raided his house. Nothing.

1063
00:59:53,323 --> 00:59:55,883
[Owen] This guy's the mole?
And you-- you got him?

1064
00:59:55,992 --> 00:59:56,959
We got him.

1065
00:59:58,361 --> 01:00:04,163
So, then... what?
We're just... We're good?

1066
01:00:04,267 --> 01:00:06,030
Well, not entirely.

1067
01:00:06,135 --> 01:00:09,935
We, uh, got some new Intel
on the Soviet progress,

1068
01:00:10,039 --> 01:00:13,099
and it turns out they're doing better
than we thought.

1069
01:00:13,209 --> 01:00:18,203
It looks like they could possibly make it
to the Moon by the end of '69.

1070
01:00:18,314 --> 01:00:23,946
Which means that we need to be done
by April, at the latest.

1071
01:00:24,053 --> 01:00:27,045
Yeah, that puts us
on a pretty tight timeline.

1072
01:00:27,156 --> 01:00:29,386
[Matt on tape] They know we're here.
We're allowed to be here, okay?

1073
01:00:29,492 --> 01:00:30,459
Relax.

1074
01:00:30,560 --> 01:00:31,618
Hi.

1075
01:00:32,662 --> 01:00:33,629
[car engine starts]

1076
01:00:35,064 --> 01:00:37,965
- [tires screeching]
- [clicking]

1077
01:00:38,067 --> 01:00:39,694
[Matt] Go, go, go, go!

1078
01:00:42,071 --> 01:00:43,629
Jared, get in the car!

1079
01:00:46,309 --> 01:00:47,435
[clicking]

1080
01:01:10,867 --> 01:01:12,926
- [Matt on phone] Hello?
- Matt, we have a problem here.

1081
01:01:13,036 --> 01:01:14,162
[clicking]

1082
01:01:15,738 --> 01:01:20,004
[Lhostky]...gentleman got the contract
with, I don't know, somebody.

1083
01:01:20,109 --> 01:01:22,339
This is who they say
the mole was.

1084
01:01:22,445 --> 01:01:24,913
So we interviewed him?

1085
01:01:25,014 --> 01:01:28,347
Yeah, over a year ago.

1086
01:01:28,451 --> 01:01:30,146
Remember when you asked me
to find out

1087
01:01:30,253 --> 01:01:32,813
- who was on the phone with Webb?
- Of course.

1088
01:01:32,922 --> 01:01:34,890
- I did.
- [clicking]

1089
01:01:34,991 --> 01:01:36,925
[Lhostky]
...second burn to the lunar surface.

1090
01:01:37,026 --> 01:01:39,187
Then we can go in after that for 250.

1091
01:01:39,295 --> 01:01:41,661
[Webb]
250 seconds is all we can do?

1092
01:01:41,764 --> 01:01:43,994
[Lhotsky]
That's the maximum, and you know that...

1093
01:01:44,100 --> 01:01:45,590
[Webb]
Did you talk to TRW?

1094
01:01:45,702 --> 01:01:49,194
[Lhotsky] Yeah. And you know how they
are about their fuels.

1095
01:01:49,305 --> 01:01:50,932
- So we are in trouble...
- Grumman...

1096
01:01:51,040 --> 01:01:52,405
[recording stops]

1097
01:01:52,508 --> 01:01:53,839
What does this mean?

1098
01:01:56,245 --> 01:02:01,740
So the mole knew that we couldn't make it
to the Moon for over a year?

1099
01:02:03,853 --> 01:02:06,048
I don't think so.

1100
01:02:06,155 --> 01:02:08,123
I don't think
that Lhotsky's the mole.

1101
01:02:08,224 --> 01:02:11,819
I don't think Lhotsky
was outside the studio.

1102
01:02:11,928 --> 01:02:14,761
I mean, Lhotsky knows that we can't make
it to the Moon, so maybe they--

1103
01:02:14,864 --> 01:02:17,731
He wouldn't cooperate and they had
to make him a fall guy

1104
01:02:17,834 --> 01:02:19,768
- by saying that he's the mole.
- They?

1105
01:02:21,170 --> 01:02:22,330
Yeah.

1106
01:02:22,438 --> 01:02:25,271
- What do-- what do you mean?
- The CIA.

1107
01:02:25,374 --> 01:02:29,140
Okay, well, then who's outside
the studio following us?

1108
01:02:29,245 --> 01:02:31,076
CIA agents.

1109
01:02:31,180 --> 01:02:34,047
That's why Boles
didn't shoot them.

1110
01:02:34,150 --> 01:02:35,708
They're all
working together.

1111
01:02:35,818 --> 01:02:38,184
They're all watching us,
and they're lying to us.

1112
01:02:38,287 --> 01:02:39,754
For what?
For what purpose?

1113
01:02:39,856 --> 01:02:43,292
They know everything that we're doing.
Why... This doesn't make any sense.

1114
01:02:43,392 --> 01:02:46,225
There's no reason
for them to be following us.

1115
01:02:46,329 --> 01:02:47,956
You-- Have you--

1116
01:02:48,064 --> 01:02:50,931
Have you heard
of a conspiracy theory before?

1117
01:02:51,033 --> 01:02:54,264
Yeah.
I think we're in one.

1118
01:03:55,731 --> 01:03:57,460
[Matt] Okay, leg out!

1119
01:03:57,567 --> 01:03:58,829
[camera clicking]

1120
01:03:58,935 --> 01:04:00,061
[Jared] That
doesn't look real.

1121
01:04:00,169 --> 01:04:01,431
Okay, you know what we'll do?

1122
01:04:01,537 --> 01:04:04,131
Jump on the count of three.
Ready?

1123
01:04:04,240 --> 01:04:05,366
I'm bringing the bounce in.

1124
01:04:05,474 --> 01:04:06,873
[Owen] That's a big jump.

1125
01:04:06,976 --> 01:04:10,070
Come on, you're supposed to be
Neil Armstrong. He's brave. Ready?

1126
01:04:10,179 --> 01:04:11,771
- [latch clicking]
- There we go.

1127
01:04:14,884 --> 01:04:15,976
Uh, change the background.

1128
01:04:20,590 --> 01:04:21,682
One more.

1129
01:04:24,427 --> 01:04:25,394
How about that?

1130
01:04:25,494 --> 01:04:27,291
- [camera clicking]
- Great.

1131
01:04:27,396 --> 01:04:28,920
That's great.

1132
01:04:29,031 --> 01:04:32,398
What are we getting in the reflection
of his helmet? Am I in it?

1133
01:04:32,501 --> 01:04:33,991
[Jared] We'll have
to replace that after.

1134
01:04:46,215 --> 01:04:48,080
- [Matt] That looks great.
- [Jared] And then you just...

1135
01:04:48,184 --> 01:04:49,151
We have to repress this.

1136
01:04:49,252 --> 01:04:51,186
Put that on an animation stand
and reshoot it.

1137
01:04:51,287 --> 01:04:53,915
This is the original
from the sound stage.

1138
01:04:54,023 --> 01:04:55,957
And the crater textures
are added after.

1139
01:04:56,058 --> 01:04:58,253
Getting rid of the details
in the studio.

1140
01:04:58,361 --> 01:05:00,989
You go in and you black out the areas
with litho ink.

1141
01:05:01,097 --> 01:05:06,296
Let's move this a little bit further down,
because it seems a little too square.

1142
01:05:06,402 --> 01:05:07,892
- Square to camera?
- Yeah.

1143
01:05:08,004 --> 01:05:09,130
Sure.

1144
01:05:13,876 --> 01:05:15,309
Wow.

1145
01:05:15,411 --> 01:05:16,844
[no audio]

1146
01:05:28,391 --> 01:05:31,554
- Ready?
- [chuckling] That's good. Yeah, go.

1147
01:05:31,661 --> 01:05:32,992
[Matt laughing]

1148
01:05:33,095 --> 01:05:35,655
- It works.
- Yes!

1149
01:05:37,600 --> 01:05:38,589
This is amazing!
Go again.

1150
01:05:38,701 --> 01:05:41,226
- [Owen] Matt.
- Yes?

1151
01:05:41,337 --> 01:05:42,827
- Have you seen this?
- Have you seen this?

1152
01:05:42,939 --> 01:05:45,908
Do it again! Do it again!
Owen, look, look.

1153
01:05:46,008 --> 01:05:47,873
Hammer, feather.

1154
01:05:47,977 --> 01:05:49,945
Drop!
Galileo was right.

1155
01:05:50,046 --> 01:05:53,277
Dude, I just put
a weight in it. What?

1156
01:05:53,382 --> 01:05:57,443
"NASA Scientist Dies."
It's from this morning's paper.

1157
01:06:00,056 --> 01:06:02,957
- Well, what the--
- Matt, it's Lhotsky.

1158
01:06:03,059 --> 01:06:04,185
What?

1159
01:06:04,293 --> 01:06:07,592
Boles.
He must've known about it.

1160
01:06:07,697 --> 01:06:09,392
Listen, think
why Lhotsky's dead.

1161
01:06:09,498 --> 01:06:11,966
Obviously, he was talking to Webb,
so they killed him.

1162
01:06:12,068 --> 01:06:13,262
They're going to kill me--

1163
01:06:13,369 --> 01:06:15,303
- We don't know why that guy's dead.
- Yes, we do.

1164
01:06:15,404 --> 01:06:17,167
"They're going to kill me"?
What are you talking about?

1165
01:06:17,273 --> 01:06:19,332
They're going to kill us both,
they're going to kill the astronauts.

1166
01:06:19,442 --> 01:06:21,342
- I'm sure--
- Anyone who knows about this.

1167
01:06:21,444 --> 01:06:23,912
I'm sure Lhotsky knew too much and so
they got rid of him. Okay? That's it.

1168
01:06:24,013 --> 01:06:26,345
Right! Right!
That's what I'm talking about!

1169
01:06:26,449 --> 01:06:28,679
He was the mole, okay?

1170
01:06:28,784 --> 01:06:32,015
No, no, they're tying off loose ends!

1171
01:06:32,121 --> 01:06:34,021
Yeah, and so who else is
gonna die, huh?

1172
01:06:34,123 --> 01:06:36,648
They're gonna kill Jim Webb?
The head of NASA? He knows, too!

1173
01:06:36,759 --> 01:06:39,227
Maybe. Maybe.
You don't think they would?

1174
01:06:39,328 --> 01:06:41,956
[laughs] No! Okay, put the suit on
and get ready, all right?

1175
01:06:42,064 --> 01:06:43,622
Shut the fuck up.

1176
01:06:50,039 --> 01:06:51,006
[sniffs]

1177
01:06:53,175 --> 01:06:54,199
[sniffs]

1178
01:06:56,278 --> 01:06:57,245
[sighs]

1179
01:06:58,481 --> 01:07:01,609
There's a glob of something on the--
on the glass, Owen. Could you get it?

1180
01:07:03,085 --> 01:07:06,054
No, it's right-- No, you didn't get it.
It's right there.

1181
01:07:06,155 --> 01:07:08,646
Right-- right there.

1182
01:07:08,758 --> 01:07:11,318
[Boles] What-- what are you doing?
It's just a test.

1183
01:07:11,427 --> 01:07:13,361
Boles, I don't take orders from you!

1184
01:07:13,462 --> 01:07:15,521
- Oh, really?
- [Matt] Guys, come on.

1185
01:07:15,631 --> 01:07:18,156
Yeah, I don't take orders from someone
who's trying to get us killed.

1186
01:07:18,267 --> 01:07:20,030
- Owen, Owen, Owen. Drop it.
- Who's trying to get you killed?

1187
01:07:20,136 --> 01:07:21,660
- He let them get away.
- No, he didn't--

1188
01:07:21,771 --> 01:07:22,965
Right?
He let them get away!

1189
01:07:23,072 --> 01:07:24,562
- That's what you did.
- Oh, really?

1190
01:07:24,673 --> 01:07:26,607
- Yes, you missed on purpose!
- [Matt] Hey, whoa, whoa, whoa!

1191
01:07:26,709 --> 01:07:29,177
What... What are you doing?
What are you doing? We're friends.

1192
01:07:29,278 --> 01:07:30,711
- Who are they?
- We're friends.

1193
01:07:30,813 --> 01:07:33,714
- Who are they? Is it Brackett? The CIA?
- Oh, you think that's your friend?

1194
01:07:33,816 --> 01:07:36,341
Why don't you tell him about how
you've been calling Brackett every day,

1195
01:07:36,452 --> 01:07:40,047
trying to get Johnson thrown
off the mission? Tell him that!

1196
01:07:40,156 --> 01:07:42,351
- What are you talking about?
- Hey, ask your friend.

1197
01:07:47,763 --> 01:07:49,025
Okay, hold on.

1198
01:07:49,131 --> 01:07:51,599
Tell him. Tell him.

1199
01:08:00,910 --> 01:08:02,878
♪♪

1200
01:08:09,718 --> 01:08:12,209
[Kennedy on recording]
We choose to go to the Moon.

1201
01:08:12,321 --> 01:08:14,482
We choose to go to the Moon--

1202
01:08:14,590 --> 01:08:16,558
[applause on recording]

1203
01:08:20,696 --> 01:08:23,164
We choose to go to the Moon
in this decade

1204
01:08:23,265 --> 01:08:25,165
and do the other things.

1205
01:08:25,267 --> 01:08:28,668
Not because they are easy,
but because they are hard.

1206
01:08:28,771 --> 01:08:32,730
Because that goal will serve
to organize and measure

1207
01:08:32,842 --> 01:08:36,437
the best of our energies and skills.

1208
01:08:36,545 --> 01:08:40,242
Because that challenge is one
that we're willing to accept,

1209
01:08:40,349 --> 01:08:43,250
one we are unwilling to postpone,

1210
01:08:43,352 --> 01:08:46,116
and one we intend to win,
and the others, too.

1211
01:08:46,222 --> 01:08:48,190
[applause]

1212
01:08:53,429 --> 01:08:55,488
We shall send to the Moon,

1213
01:08:55,598 --> 01:09:01,264
240, 000 miles away from the control
station in Houston,

1214
01:09:01,370 --> 01:09:03,201
a giant rocket,

1215
01:09:03,305 --> 01:09:08,106
more than 300 feet tall,
the length of this football field,

1216
01:09:08,210 --> 01:09:13,079
made of new metal alloys,
some of which have not yet been invented,

1217
01:09:13,182 --> 01:09:16,049
capable of standing heat and stresses

1218
01:09:16,152 --> 01:09:19,451
several times more than have ever
been experienced,

1219
01:09:19,555 --> 01:09:24,322
on an untried mission
to an unknown celestial body,

1220
01:09:24,426 --> 01:09:27,623
and then return it safely to Earth,

1221
01:09:27,730 --> 01:09:32,497
re-entering the atmosphere
at speeds of over 25, 000 miles per hour.

1222
01:09:32,601 --> 01:09:37,800
And do all this... And do all this
and do it right, and do it first,

1223
01:09:37,907 --> 01:09:39,898
before this decade is out,

1224
01:09:40,009 --> 01:09:41,840
then we must be bold.

1225
01:09:41,944 --> 01:09:43,912
[applause]

1226
01:09:45,181 --> 01:09:47,376
And therefore, as we set sail,

1227
01:09:47,483 --> 01:09:52,079
we ask God's blessing on the most
hazardous and dangerous

1228
01:09:52,188 --> 01:09:55,385
and greatest adventure on which man
has ever embarked.

1229
01:09:55,491 --> 01:09:56,719
Thank you.

1230
01:09:56,825 --> 01:09:58,793
[applause]

1231
01:10:18,314 --> 01:10:20,179
[Boles] So this is the only copy?

1232
01:10:20,282 --> 01:10:24,480
Yeah. So... now what?
We just bring it to Brackett?

1233
01:10:24,587 --> 01:10:28,318
Oh, I'll take it to Brackett.
You stay here and clean up.

1234
01:10:28,424 --> 01:10:29,891
Clean up what?

1235
01:10:29,992 --> 01:10:35,157
Clean up the studio.
Destroy everything.

1236
01:10:35,264 --> 01:10:36,629
What if we--
What if we need that stuff?

1237
01:10:36,732 --> 01:10:39,792
We won't. Good work.

1238
01:10:39,902 --> 01:10:42,803
- Thanks.
- I'll see you soon.

1239
01:10:42,905 --> 01:10:44,031
Hey, Boles.

1240
01:10:44,139 --> 01:10:46,972
[stammers]
Lhotsky wasn't the mole, was he?

1241
01:10:53,782 --> 01:10:55,113
What are you talking about?

1242
01:10:58,921 --> 01:11:01,446
[chuckles]
Yeah, I don't...

1243
01:11:01,557 --> 01:11:03,184
I don't know.

1244
01:11:03,292 --> 01:11:05,817
I've been working on
this too long. I'm sorry.

1245
01:11:05,928 --> 01:11:09,591
Well, get some rest.
I'll see you soon.

1246
01:11:09,698 --> 01:11:11,632
- [door opens]
- Bye, buddy.

1247
01:11:13,302 --> 01:11:14,599
[door closes]

1248
01:11:17,706 --> 01:11:18,673
[sighs]

1249
01:11:37,660 --> 01:11:39,093
[clicking]

1250
01:11:40,329 --> 01:11:41,455
[whirring]

1251
01:11:54,009 --> 01:11:55,135
[clicking]

1252
01:12:14,563 --> 01:12:15,860
[film winding]

1253
01:12:18,500 --> 01:12:22,960
He's gonna spot one of our guys pretending
to be a rocket scientist instantly.

1254
01:12:23,072 --> 01:12:27,532
We need to send people who are gonna look
like they have no idea what's going on.

1255
01:12:27,643 --> 01:12:28,940
[film winding]

1256
01:12:39,021 --> 01:12:41,080
They can't make it to the Moon.

1257
01:12:42,858 --> 01:12:44,849
I'm gonna tell you what they said.

1258
01:12:48,097 --> 01:12:50,429
[indistinct talking]

1259
01:12:51,467 --> 01:12:53,196
[Owen] ...an ethical problem
with this at all?

1260
01:12:53,302 --> 01:12:55,896
- ♪ You don't know... ♪
- [clicking]

1261
01:13:00,042 --> 01:13:01,270
[clicking]

1262
01:13:01,377 --> 01:13:03,470
[music playing on tape]

1263
01:13:04,513 --> 01:13:05,639
[Owen] He let them get away!
That's what you did.

1264
01:13:05,748 --> 01:13:07,579
- [Boles] Oh, really?
- [Owen] Yes, you missed on purpose!

1265
01:13:07,683 --> 01:13:09,514
[Matt] Hey, whoa, whoa, whoa!
What-- what are you doing?

1266
01:13:09,618 --> 01:13:11,051
What are you doing?
We're friends!

1267
01:13:11,153 --> 01:13:13,451
- [Owen] Who are they? Who are...
- [Matt] We're friends.

1268
01:13:16,425 --> 01:13:18,154
[Boles] What, you think
that's your friend?

1269
01:13:18,260 --> 01:13:20,023
- Who, Brackett? The CIA?
- Why don't you tell him about how...

1270
01:13:24,666 --> 01:13:26,634
[marker squeaking]

1271
01:13:31,240 --> 01:13:32,969
[breathing heavily]

1272
01:13:46,422 --> 01:13:47,548
[panting]

1273
01:13:54,530 --> 01:13:55,758
[car engine revving]

1274
01:14:00,202 --> 01:14:01,726
[engine stops]

1275
01:14:01,837 --> 01:14:03,134
[car door opens]

1276
01:14:05,707 --> 01:14:07,004
[car door closes]

1277
01:14:07,109 --> 01:14:12,672
Hey, Julie.
Can I borrow your husband?

1278
01:14:12,781 --> 01:14:15,750
- He what? Oh.
- Simon's asleep. Inside.

1279
01:14:17,219 --> 01:14:20,950
- I can go inside, so you guys can talk.
- You can stay outside.

1280
01:14:21,056 --> 01:14:24,492
No, I don't need to talk.
I wanna know if, um...

1281
01:14:24,593 --> 01:14:28,791
If you wanna... We're-- we're going
to get rid of the stuff from work.

1282
01:14:31,166 --> 01:14:33,760
You can go if you want.

1283
01:14:33,869 --> 01:14:35,166
No, I'm going to stay here.

1284
01:14:39,575 --> 01:14:42,373
How's Simon? Are you guys excited
about the big launch?

1285
01:14:42,478 --> 01:14:43,945
[chuckles]

1286
01:14:46,081 --> 01:14:49,676
Okay. Have a good afternoon.

1287
01:14:49,785 --> 01:14:51,582
[Julie] Thanks. You, too.
I'll see you soon, okay?

1288
01:14:51,687 --> 01:14:52,654
Yeah, bye.

1289
01:15:06,001 --> 01:15:06,968
[Cronkite] Good morning.

1290
01:15:07,069 --> 01:15:11,904
It's T-minus one hour, 29 minutes
and 53 seconds and counting.

1291
01:15:12,007 --> 01:15:15,135
In just an hour and a half,
if all goes well,

1292
01:15:15,244 --> 01:15:18,736
Apollo 11 astronauts
Armstrong, Aldrin, and Collins

1293
01:15:18,847 --> 01:15:22,078
are to lift off
from Pad 39-A out there

1294
01:15:22,184 --> 01:15:25,517
on the voyage man
always has dreamed about.

1295
01:15:25,621 --> 01:15:27,486
Next stop for them,
the Moon.

1296
01:15:28,524 --> 01:15:31,823
And we are all about to witness
the fulfillment of that promise

1297
01:15:31,927 --> 01:15:35,988
that President Kennedy made
at Rice University Stadium in Texas,

1298
01:15:36,098 --> 01:15:39,556
on September 12, 1962.

1299
01:15:39,668 --> 01:15:41,761
We passed 10,000 odd cars

1300
01:15:41,870 --> 01:15:44,532
parked around the Gate-1 area
at 4:00 a.m. when we got here.

1301
01:15:44,640 --> 01:15:47,939
Cars from every state,
with little kids staring wide-eyed,

1302
01:15:48,043 --> 01:15:50,273
and we saw teenagers
with telescopes.

1303
01:15:51,313 --> 01:15:53,247
It was a very moving scene for me,

1304
01:15:53,348 --> 01:15:57,148
because Americans cared then,
I think, and they care now.

1305
01:15:57,252 --> 01:16:01,313
And it says, "Good luck... good luck,
Apollo 11" engraved in the sand.

1306
01:16:01,423 --> 01:16:05,189
All going very smoothly here
with the count.

1307
01:16:05,294 --> 01:16:07,455
[Mission Control]
T-minus 60 seconds and counting.

1308
01:16:07,563 --> 01:16:10,964
We've passed T-minus 60.
Power transfer is complete.

1309
01:16:15,037 --> 01:16:18,029
Twelve, eleven, ten, nine...

1310
01:16:18,140 --> 01:16:20,734
Ignition sequence starts.

1311
01:16:20,842 --> 01:16:26,474
Six, five, four, three, two, one.

1312
01:16:54,409 --> 01:16:57,503
[Frank Reynolds] And good afternoon
from ABC space headquarters in New York.

1313
01:16:57,613 --> 01:17:00,844
With me is our science editor,
Jules Bergman, and we are on the air today

1314
01:17:00,949 --> 01:17:05,010
to bring you a complete report
on some very, very important maneuvers

1315
01:17:05,120 --> 01:17:07,111
- to be performed by Apollo 11.
- [phone rings]

1316
01:17:07,222 --> 01:17:09,520
Basically in position to begin
the process...

1317
01:17:09,625 --> 01:17:11,354
- Hello?
- [Owen] Matt?

1318
01:17:11,460 --> 01:17:13,257
[chuckling] Are you--
are you seeing this right now?

1319
01:17:13,362 --> 01:17:16,024
[Owen] Matt, they're not dead.
The CIA lied to us.

1320
01:17:16,131 --> 01:17:17,359
[stammering]
Wait, what?

1321
01:17:17,466 --> 01:17:20,902
[Owen] The men following us at the studio
are outside my house.

1322
01:17:21,003 --> 01:17:23,267
- Are you sure?
- Yes, meet me at your motel.

1323
01:17:23,372 --> 01:17:25,272
- [line disconnects]
- [dial tone]

1324
01:17:31,146 --> 01:17:33,171
What the hell?

1325
01:17:33,281 --> 01:17:34,976
[knocking on door]

1326
01:17:36,251 --> 01:17:37,548
Owen?

1327
01:17:41,723 --> 01:17:42,690
Hello?

1328
01:17:57,139 --> 01:17:58,834
Who's there?

1329
01:17:58,940 --> 01:18:00,407
Oh, shit.

1330
01:18:02,010 --> 01:18:04,205
Okay, okay, okay.

1331
01:18:04,312 --> 01:18:06,974
[breathing heavily]

1332
01:18:07,082 --> 01:18:10,051
Uh... Uh...

1333
01:18:12,187 --> 01:18:14,052
Where's the other car?
Where's the--

1334
01:18:14,156 --> 01:18:16,147
[Jared] Um, um, out back.
Out back.

1335
01:18:16,258 --> 01:18:18,226
[TV playing indistinct]

1336
01:18:26,068 --> 01:18:27,194
[Matt] Okay, stand back.

1337
01:18:29,571 --> 01:18:30,868
[grunting]

1338
01:18:41,183 --> 01:18:43,151
[groaning]

1339
01:18:48,824 --> 01:18:50,951
[breathing heavily]

1340
01:18:51,059 --> 01:18:52,026
Sorry.

1341
01:18:52,127 --> 01:18:54,288
[man on TV]...in a delirium
of enthusiasm today...

1342
01:18:55,964 --> 01:18:57,932
[panting]

1343
01:19:00,102 --> 01:19:01,763
Come on.

1344
01:19:01,870 --> 01:19:02,837
Come on, come on.

1345
01:19:11,480 --> 01:19:13,107
Come on, Owen.
Come on!

1346
01:19:23,225 --> 01:19:24,749
[Jared] Matt!

1347
01:19:26,027 --> 01:19:27,654
What?

1348
01:19:27,763 --> 01:19:28,730
There's a car!

1349
01:19:38,840 --> 01:19:40,501
Jared, run!

1350
01:19:48,150 --> 01:19:50,380
- Shit.
- Go, go, go.

1351
01:19:50,485 --> 01:19:53,113
[radio playing indistinct]

1352
01:20:00,896 --> 01:20:01,863
Andy, hold on.

1353
01:20:10,305 --> 01:20:11,272
Fuck!

1354
01:20:19,114 --> 01:20:21,048
They're right behind us.
They're right behind us.

1355
01:20:21,149 --> 01:20:23,117
[tires screeching]

1356
01:20:27,322 --> 01:20:29,381
Get their faces!
Get their faces, Andy! Get their faces!

1357
01:20:29,491 --> 01:20:31,459
[Andy]
This is fucking crazy!

1358
01:20:37,432 --> 01:20:40,162
- Oh, God!
- Oh, Christ!

1359
01:20:45,040 --> 01:20:46,837
- [Andy] He's got a gun!
- What?

1360
01:20:46,942 --> 01:20:49,809
- He's got a fucking gun!
- Okay, duck, duck, duck!

1361
01:20:56,585 --> 01:20:58,212
[groans]
Oh, shit.

1362
01:21:00,288 --> 01:21:02,347
[panting]

1363
01:21:03,992 --> 01:21:06,222
[shooting continues]

1364
01:21:10,065 --> 01:21:11,930
[engine backfires]

1365
01:21:12,033 --> 01:21:13,364
[Andy]
What's happening?

1366
01:21:13,468 --> 01:21:15,129
- [engine stalling]
- Uh...

1367
01:21:15,237 --> 01:21:17,831
Oh, fuck. Fuck!

1368
01:21:22,310 --> 01:21:23,572
Jesus!

1369
01:21:25,280 --> 01:21:26,508
[engine starts]

1370
01:21:26,615 --> 01:21:28,583
[Matt] Okay, okay.

1371
01:21:35,056 --> 01:21:37,024
[Andy] Get out of here.
Get out of here.

1372
01:21:37,125 --> 01:21:38,615
- I'm trying.
- Get out of here.

1373
01:21:40,462 --> 01:21:41,861
Dude, they're
right in front of us.

1374
01:21:41,963 --> 01:21:43,555
Yeah, I know.

1375
01:21:47,669 --> 01:21:49,193
[tires screeching]

1376
01:21:49,304 --> 01:21:50,794
They're gonna ram us,
they're gonna ram us!

1377
01:21:50,906 --> 01:21:52,498
- [gunshot]
- [Andy groans]

1378
01:21:58,079 --> 01:21:59,046
Oh!

1379
01:22:14,930 --> 01:22:17,057
[car radio continues playing indistinct]

1380
01:22:24,239 --> 01:22:25,206
Owen!

1381
01:22:26,808 --> 01:22:29,174
Owen! Owen!

1382
01:22:32,147 --> 01:22:33,114
Owen!

1383
01:22:45,694 --> 01:22:46,922
Owen!

1384
01:22:51,733 --> 01:22:52,859
[gasps]

1385
01:23:15,223 --> 01:23:16,485
[car approaching]

1386
01:25:02,297 --> 01:25:04,356
So they're not all labeled, right?

1387
01:25:04,466 --> 01:25:08,766
It goes '67, '68, '69. But not
everything's... Not everything's marked.

1388
01:25:08,870 --> 01:25:11,236
Well, you'll figure it out.

1389
01:25:11,339 --> 01:25:12,306
Hey.

1390
01:25:20,415 --> 01:25:22,406
Okay, man.

1391
01:25:22,517 --> 01:25:24,451
As soon as I know where we're going,
I'll call you.

1392
01:25:24,552 --> 01:25:25,519
Yeah.

1393
01:26:40,395 --> 01:26:41,987
- [dial tone]
- [coins tinkling]

1394
01:26:42,096 --> 01:26:43,256
[dialing phone]

1395
01:26:45,934 --> 01:26:47,663
[line ringing]

1396
01:26:51,339 --> 01:26:52,431
[man on phone]
Good evening.

1397
01:26:52,540 --> 01:26:55,566
Hello, there's a man at the end of the bar
wearing glasses.

1398
01:26:55,677 --> 01:26:57,372
Could you please give
the phone to him?

1399
01:27:02,016 --> 01:27:03,142
Telephone.

1400
01:27:09,290 --> 01:27:10,882
Hello?

1401
01:27:10,992 --> 01:27:13,119
[Matt] You're a real piece of shit,
you know that?

1402
01:27:17,465 --> 01:27:19,524
We're looking for you.
Where you been?

1403
01:27:19,634 --> 01:27:21,693
Yeah, I'll tell you what,
let's make a trade.

1404
01:27:23,304 --> 01:27:24,771
Okay.

1405
01:27:24,872 --> 01:27:27,932
My location for the names of the agents
on your kill team.

1406
01:27:29,711 --> 01:27:31,474
We don't have any kill team.

1407
01:27:31,579 --> 01:27:34,207
Yeah, well, who killed Owen
and hung him in his garage?

1408
01:27:37,852 --> 01:27:41,481
Okay. Come down to the office.
We'll discuss it.

1409
01:27:41,589 --> 01:27:43,682
[scoffs]
Yeah, I'll come in.

1410
01:27:43,791 --> 01:27:45,281
No, I'll tell you
what's gonna happen.

1411
01:27:45,393 --> 01:27:47,520
I have a film
of everything we did.

1412
01:27:47,629 --> 01:27:50,792
I have proof that the CIA conspired
to fake the Moon landing

1413
01:27:50,898 --> 01:27:52,229
and that Owen Williams is the one

1414
01:27:52,333 --> 01:27:54,267
that everybody is about to see walk
on the Moon,

1415
01:27:54,369 --> 01:27:57,304
and that you killed him
to keep it a secret!

1416
01:27:57,405 --> 01:28:01,000
I even got you planning Northwoods,
the same as I got you right now.

1417
01:28:09,517 --> 01:28:11,485
No one will take that seriously, kid.

1418
01:28:11,586 --> 01:28:12,814
Yeah, well, call my bluff.

1419
01:28:12,920 --> 01:28:15,548
My last movie's about to convince
the world we went to the Moon.

1420
01:28:16,958 --> 01:28:20,291
Then why don't I make you a deal?

1421
01:28:20,395 --> 01:28:21,919
Come back and work for us,

1422
01:28:22,030 --> 01:28:25,932
and I'll make you the head
of your own department.

1423
01:28:26,034 --> 01:28:27,399
[Matt chuckles]

1424
01:28:28,603 --> 01:28:32,596
[laughing] Yeah, how stupid
do you think I am?

1425
01:28:34,709 --> 01:28:36,301
[Brackett sighs]

1426
01:28:36,411 --> 01:28:38,140
I'll tell you what.

1427
01:28:38,246 --> 01:28:42,774
Keep the film as collateral if you don't
believe me. Just think about it.

1428
01:28:46,721 --> 01:28:48,018
[dial tone]

1429
01:29:11,779 --> 01:29:13,076
[breathing heavily]

1430
01:29:28,496 --> 01:29:32,455
[Neil Armstrong]
...the surface appears to be, uh,

1431
01:29:32,567 --> 01:29:36,333
very, very fine grained
as you get close to it.

1432
01:29:36,437 --> 01:29:41,340
It's almost like a powder...
down there, uh, it's very fine.

1433
01:29:43,644 --> 01:29:45,612
Okay, I'm going to step off the LM now.

1434
01:29:51,919 --> 01:29:54,717
That's one small step for man...

1435
01:29:57,291 --> 01:30:00,021
one giant leap for mankind.

1436
01:30:12,473 --> 01:30:13,997
And the...

1437
01:30:14,108 --> 01:30:15,200
♪♪

1438
01:30:15,309 --> 01:30:17,436
...the surface
is fine and powdery.

1439
01:30:17,545 --> 01:30:21,879
I can... I can pick
it up loosely with my toe.

1440
01:30:21,983 --> 01:30:24,975
It does adhere in fine--

1441
01:30:25,086 --> 01:30:26,519
♪ Some folks are born ♪

1442
01:30:26,621 --> 01:30:28,714
♪ Made to wave the flag ♪

1443
01:30:28,823 --> 01:30:30,984
♪ Oh, they're red, white and blue ♪

1444
01:30:32,460 --> 01:30:35,588
♪ And when the band plays
"Hail to the chief" ♪

1445
01:30:35,696 --> 01:30:39,530
♪ Ooh, they point
the cannon at you now ♪

1446
01:30:39,634 --> 01:30:43,195
♪ It ain't me, it ain't me ♪

1447
01:30:43,304 --> 01:30:46,239
♪ I ain't no senator's son, son ♪

1448
01:30:47,275 --> 01:30:50,711
